statement.p:
The expressions 3(x-4)+2 and 3x-10 are mathematically equivalent, 
even though they involve different operations.
We show this by applying the properties in sequence.

  3(x-4)+2 &= (3x-12)+2 & \text{Distributive}
   &= (3x+-12)+2 & \text{Additive Inverse}
   &= 3x+(-12+2) & \text{Associative}
   &= 3x+-10 & \text{Arithmetic}
   &= 3x-10 & \text{Subtraction}

li.p:
Divisors in the Denominator.
(\div a) \cdot (\div b) = \div(ab), 
or \displaystyle \frac{1}{a} \cdot \frac{1}{b} = \frac{1}{ab}

proof.p:
Each property results from the basic properties of addition.
The following calculations emphasize these connections.





    To show \div(ab) = (\div a) \cdot (\div b), 
    we need to show that the property of a multiplicative inverse is satisfied.
    This requires the commutative and associative properties.
    (ab) \cdot (\div a \cdot \div b) = (a \div a) \cdot (b \div b) = 1 \cdot 1 = 1.
    Written in terms of fractions, this means 
    \displaystyle \frac{1}{a} \cdot \frac{1}{b} = \frac{1}{ab}.






    Multiplication is associative and commutative.

       a \cdot \frac{b}{c} &= a (b \div c) = (a b) \div c = \frac{ab}{c}
      \frac{a}{b} \cdot \frac{c}{d} &= (a {\div b}) \cdot (c {\div d}) = (ac) \cdot ({\div b} {\div d}) = (ac) {\div(bd)} = \frac{ac}{bd}







    Division is multiplication by inverse.
    (\frac{a}{b}) \div (\frac{c}{d}) = \frac{a}{b} \cdot \frac{d}{c} = \frac{ad}{bc}






    Adding fractions applies the distributive property using the common denominator as the common factor.

      \frac{a}{b} + \frac{c}{d} &= \frac{ad}{bd} + \frac{bc}{bd} = (ad) \,{\div(bd)} + (bc)\,{\div(bd)}
      & = (ad+bc)\,{\div(bd)} = \frac{ad+bc}{bd}

statement.p:
The quotient properties for integer powers result from canceling common factors followed by counting.

   \frac{b^6}{b^2} = \frac{(bb)(bbbb)}{bb} = bbbb = b^{6-2}
   \left(\frac{b}{c}\right)^3 = \frac{b}{c} \cdot \frac{b}{c} \cdot \frac{b}{c} = \frac{b^3}{c^3}

solution.p:
Start by writing 1.2 as a product of the factors 2, 3, and 5.
1.2 = \frac{12}{10} = \frac{4(3)}{2(5)} = \frac{2(3)}{5} 
The properties of logarithms allow us to rewrite \log(1.2) as 

   \log(1.2) &= \log\left(\frac{2(3)}{5}\right) 
   &= \log(2(3)) - \log(5) & \text{(Quotient)} 
   &= \log(2) + \log(3) - \log(5) & \text{(Product)} 
    &\approx 0.30103 + 0.47712 - 0.69897 = 0.07918.

It is usually best to isolate the exponential term first.
3 \cdot 2^{3x} = 5 2^{3x} = \frac{5}{3}
We next apply the logarithm base 10 to both sides of this equation, which then allows us to apply the logarithm power rule on the left. Then we can isolate x.
\log_{10}(2^{3x}) = \log_{10}({\textstyle \frac{5}{3}}) 3x \cdot \log_{10}(2) = \log_{10}({\textstyle \frac{5}{3}}) x = \frac{\log_{10}({\textstyle \frac{5}{3}})}{3 \log_{10}(2)}

One approach is to use the inverse property, \exp(\ln(u)) = e^{\ln(u)} = u, on the factor with the power.
Then use logarithm properties to simplify (expand) the power.

   f(x) &= 4 \cdot 3^{2x} 
   &= 4 \cdot e^{\ln(3^{2x})} & \text{(Inverse)} 
   &= 4 \cdot e^{2x \ln(3)} & \text{(Power)} 
   &= 4 \cdot e^{2 \ln(3) \, x} & \text{(Commute)}

Another approach is to just rewrite the base using the inverse property, 
3 = e^{\ln(3)}, 
and then finish by using properties of powers.

   f(x) &= 4 \cdot 3^{2x} 
   &= 4 \cdot (e^{\ln(3)})^{2x} & \text{(Inverse)} 
   &= 4 \cdot e^{2x \ln(3)} & \text{(Power of Product)} 
   &= 4 \cdot e^{2 \ln(3) \, x} & \text{(Commute)}
